All,
     I have started using some code internally and would like to run the
idea past the JUnit group as a whole.  We know the value of performing test
cases, we just seldom actually take the time to implement them in our
hectic schedule.  So I have put together the frame work for automatically
generating test cases for any class, any method.  Here is a sample Java
file:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
package test;

/**
 * @testable
 */
public class DocletTest {

     public DocletTest() {
     }

     /**
      * @test-method
      * @test-case 4
      * @assert 16
      * @test-case 5
      * @assert 25
      * @test-case 6
      * @assert 36
      */
     public int square(int a) {
          return a*a;
     }

     /**
      * @test-method
      * @test-case &quot;Hello World!&quot;
      * @assert &quot;!dlroW olleH&quot;
      */
     public String reverse(String a) {
          char[] temp = new char[a.length()];
          char[] orig = a.toCharArray();
          int j = 0;
          for(int i = orig.length-1; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
               temp[j++] = orig[i];
          }
          return new String(temp);
     }
}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Using the Doclet API, special javadoc tags are placed throughout the code.
The first tag &#39;@testable&#39; indicates that we want a test case generated.
The Doclet then scans the methods and will generate a testxxx method for
each method with an &#39;@test-method&#39; tag.  The &#39;@test-case xxx&#39; and &#39;@assert
xxx&#39; tags work together as the input to your method, and the expected
output.  So the result of processing this file is as follows:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
/**
 * Generated TestSuite for DocletTest. Do not edit!
 */
package test;

import junit.framework.*;
import junit.extensions.*;


public class DocletTestTestCase extends TestCase {

     DocletTest test;

public DocletTestTestCase(String name) {
     super(name);
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
     junit.textui.TestRunner.run(suite());
}

public static Test suite() {
     return new TestSuite(DocletTestTestCase.class);
}

protected void setUp() {
}

protected void tearDown() {}


public void testsquare() {

     try {
          test = new DocletTest();
          int a  = 4;

          int returntype = test.square(a);

          assert(returntype == 16);

     }
     catch(Exception e) {
          fail(&quot;Could not invoke method square on
test.DocletTestTestCase.&quot;);
     }

     try {
          test = new DocletTest();
          int a  = 5;

          int returntype = test.square(a);

          assert(returntype == 25);

     }
     catch(Exception e) {
          fail(&quot;Could not invoke method square on
test.DocletTestTestCase.&quot;);
     }

     try {
          test = new DocletTest();
          int a  = 6;

          int returntype = test.square(a);

          assert(returntype == 36);

     }
     catch(Exception e) {
          fail(&quot;Could not invoke method square on
test.DocletTestTestCase.&quot;);
     }

}

public void testreverse() {

     try {
          test = new DocletTest();
          java.lang.String a  = &quot;Hello World!&quot;;

          java.lang.String returntype = test.reverse(a);

          assert(returntype.equals(&quot;!dlroW olleH&quot;));

     }
     catch(Exception e) {
          fail(&quot;Could not invoke method reverse on
test.DocletTestTestCase.&quot;);
     }

}


}
